2025 Elections: Market Votes Data

2024-10-29

Exploratory Data Analysis

Summary of Key Findings

  • Akbayan does not have areas that would be considered clear or strong bailiwicks. Instead, Akbayan’s votes were spread out as the party garnered at least one vote in 1,596 cities/municipalities.
  • Akbayan tends to fare better in more competitive localities. One measure of competitiveness is the Herfindahl-Hirschman Index (HHI), which is calculated as the sum of the squares of the market shares (in this case, the vote shares) of all party-lists in a given city/municipality. The formula is:

\[ HHI = \sum_{i=1}^n s_i^2 \]

where \(s^2\) is the vote share of party-list \(i\) in a city/municipality and \(N\) is the total number of party-lists in that city/municipality.

  • Akbayan performs best in localities with HHI not greater than 0.25. Low HHI values indicate a highly competitive environment. This occurs when many party-lists have relatively equal shares of the votes. High HHI values suggest concentration or dominance, meaning one or a few party-lists hold a large share of the votes.
  • Akbayan performs best in localities when there is no dominant party-list garnering over 40% of PL votes.
  • Akbayan’s performance in a locality correlates with Chel Diokno’s senatorial performance in the same locality. The correlation also exists between Akbayan’s performance and Risa Hontiveros’ senatorial performance, albeit to a weaker extent. When controlling for both variables, it seems that Chel’s performance in an area was more predictive of Akbayan’s performance.
lm_chel <- lm(akbayan_vote_share ~ chel_ratio01 + hhi + log(total_plvotes),
   data = vote_strat_data)
lm_risa <- lm(akbayan_vote_share ~ risa_ratio01 + hhi + log(total_plvotes),
   data = vote_strat_data)
lm_chelrisa <- lm(akbayan_vote_share ~ chel_ratio01 + risa_ratio01 + hhi + log(total_plvotes),
   data = vote_strat_data)

Identifying Strategic Areas

Filtering and Sorting Algorithm to Identify Market Areas

1. Target Chel Voters

  • Given that Chel is the party’s first nominee, we can leverage voters who were already inclined to vote for Chel in the previous election.
  • To be conservative, we can subtract the votes garnered by the highest vote-getting PL from the number of Chel voters in an area:

\[ MarketVotes = Votes_{Chel} - Votes_{Highest PL} \]

2. Apply Filters for Competitiveness

  • Non-zero market votes, i.e., Chel’s votes must be higher than the votes of the highest vote-getting PL
  • Chel ranked at least 18th in the Senate race
  • Herfindahl-Hirschman Index (HHI) not greater than 0.25
  • Percent share of the highest vote-getting PL not greater than 25%

3. Apply sorting based on voter density

  • Sort based on the areas with the largest number of market votes

Maximizing non-Chel Markets - Risa Voters

1. Target Risa Voters

  • Outside of areas where Chel performed relatively well, we can create a targetting algorithm based on Risa’s voters.
  • To be conservative, we can subtract the votes garnered by the highest vote-getting PL from the number of Risa voters in an area

\[ MarketVotes = Votes_{Risa} - Votes_{Highest PL} \]

2. Apply Filters for Competitiveness

  • Non-zero market votes, i.e., Risa’s votes must be higher than the votes of the highest vote-getting PL
  • Risa ranked at least 12th in the Senate race
  • Chel ranked at below 18th in the Senate race
  • Herfindahl-Hirschman Index (HHI) not greater than 0.25
  • Percent share of the highest vote-getting PL not greater than 25%

3. Apply sorting based on voter density

  • Sort based on the areas with the largest number of market votes
